@c ================================================================================
@node Notes on Time Complexity
@section Notes on Time Complexity

Most lookup operations, and most ``point update'' operations (which update a single element or
pair), have O(log @i{n}) time complexity.  In these cases, @i{n} refers to the size of the
collection.

FSet has several operations, such as @code{union} on sets, that combine two collections.  These
operations are normally O(@i{n}), but there are two exceptions.  On one hand, if the collections are
not of the same type and organization, more generic methods are invoked that are O(@i{n} log @i{n}).
On the other, under some circumstances (when they are of the same type and organization), they can
take O(log @i{n}) time.  The latter occurs if they are @dfn{historically related}: one is the result
of making a small number of point updates on the 6other, or they are both the result of making such
updates on a common ancestor.  Under such circumstances, their internal trees will be largely
shared; the implementations detect and exploit this sharing to elide most of the work.

Also, even when these operations do take O(@i{n}) time, there's the question of exactly what @i{n}
corresponds to.  For many of these operations, in the worst case, it's the sum of the two sizes, but
in typical cases it's often closer to the minimum of the two.  For some operations, notably
intersection (including map and bag intersection and bag product), it's the minimum even in the
worst case.  For asymmetrical operations like set-difference, it's the size of the left operand.


@c ================================================================================
@node Sets
@section Sets

A set is an unordered collection of values without duplicates, called its elements or members, with
efficient operations to add or remove a value and to test whether the set contains a value.  Adding
a value to a set that already contains it, or removing one from a set that does not contain it,
results in the same set.

Although sets are conceptually unordered, FSet imposes an order for its own purposes.  The WB
implementation allows you to @href{Custom Comparison and Hash Functions, control} this ordering.

The default implementation of sets is currently CHAMP (@code{ch-set}).  The WB implementation
(@code{wb-set}) is also available.

@deftp {Data type} set
The abstract class for FSet functional sets.  Subclass of @code{collection}.
@end deftp

@defun set? x
Returns true iff @var{x} is an FSet functional set.
@end defun

@deftp {Data type} transient-set
The abstract class for FSet transient sets.  Subclass of @code{transient-collection}.
@end deftp

@defun transient-set? x
Returns true iff @var{x} is an FSet transient set.
@end defun

@defun empty-set
Constructor function.  Returns an empty set of the default implementation, currently @code{ch-set},
and the default organization.
@end defun

@anchor{Macro set}
@defmac set @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a set of the default implementation, currently @code{ch-set}, and the
default organization, according to the supplied argument subforms.  Each argument subform can be an
expression, whose value will be an element of the result set; or a list of the form @code{($
@var{expression})}, in which case the expression must evaluate to a set, all of whose elements
become elements of the result set.
@end defmac

@anchor{Type ch-set}
@deftp {Data type} ch-set
Functional sets implemented using CHAMP trees.  Subclass of @code{set}.  These print as:

@example
##@{ @i{e0} @i{e1} ... @}[@i{compare-fn}]
@end example

Note the double @code{#}, which indicates CHAMP.  The comparison function is printed only if it is not
@code{compare}.
@end deftp

@defun ch-set? x
Returns true iff @var{x} is an FSet functional CHAMP set.
@end defun

@defun empty-ch-set @r{&key} compare-fn-name
Constructor function.  Returns an empty @code{ch-set}.  By default, it will be ordered by
@code{compare}.  To use a custom ordering, supply the comparison function name (a symbol) as
@code{compare-fn-name}; a hash function must have been defined for it using
@href{Macro define-hash-function, @code{define-hash-function}}.
@end defun

@anchor{Macro ch-set}
@defmac ch-set @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-set} according to the supplied argument subforms.  See
@href{Macro set, @code{set}@comma{} above} for the interpretation of @var{subforms}.
@end defmac

@defmac ch-custom-set compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{ch-set} with a custom organization, according to the supplied
argument subforms.  @code{compare-fn-name} must be a symbol naming the desired comparison function;
a hash function must have been defined for it using @href{Macro define-hash-function,
@code{define-hash-function}}.  See @href{Macro set, @code{set}@comma{} above} for the interpretation of
@var{subforms}.
@end defmac

@anchor{Type wb-set}
@deftp {Data type} wb-set
Functional sets implemented using WB-trees.  Subclass of @code{set}.  These print as:

@example
#@{ @i{e0} @i{e1} ... @}[@i{compare-fn}]
@end example

Note the single @code{#}, which indicates WB.  The comparison function is printed only if it is not
@code{compare}.
@end deftp

@defun wb-set? x
Returns true iff @var{x} is an FSet functional WB-tree set.
@end defun

@defun empty-wb-set @r{&key} compare-fn-name
Constructor function.  Returns an empty wb-set.  By default, it will be ordered by
@code{compare}.  To use a custom ordering, supply the comparison function name (a symbol) as
@code{compare-fn-name}.
@end defun

@anchor{Macro wb-set}
@defmac wb-set @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{wb-set} according to the supplied argument subforms.  See
@href{Macro set, @code{set}@comma{} above} for the interpretation of @var{subforms}.
@end defmac

@defmac wb-custom-set compare-fn-name @r{&rest} subforms
Constructor macro.  Constructs a @code{wb-set} with a custom organization, according to the supplied
argument subforms.  @code{compare-fn-name} must be a symbol naming the desired comparison function.
See @href{Macro set, @code{set}@comma{} above} for the interpretation of @var{subforms}.
@end defmac

